<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12032f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12032f">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12032f"> 32(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ goglu (pisteur)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">215-7: La foule descend, tumultueuse et bruyante vers les h&ocirc;tels; elle s&apos;&eacute;coule par la rue &eacute;troite; elle suit les remparts; il y a des rencontres entre ceux qui montent vers l&apos;Abbaye et ceux qui en sortent; &agrave; certains passages r&eacute;tr&eacute;cis, &agrave; des coudes brusques, le long des degr&eacute;s, ces rencontres deviennent des collisions. Toutes ces conversations produisent une rumeur &eacute;trange: soudain un cri s&apos;&eacute;l&egrave;ve: &ldquo; Au voleur! au voleur! On m&apos;a fait mon portemonnaie!&rdquo;]&hellip; <p>Consolez-vous, madame. Vous e&ucirc;tes, au Moyen Age, des s&oelig;urs d&apos;infortune; aux &eacute;poques lointaines des grands p&egrave;lerinages, la Petite Egypte s&apos;abattait aussi sur les foules d&eacute;votes au grand Archange; jongleurs, baladins, tire-bourses, vide goussets, faux &eacute;clop&eacute;s, aveugles&hellip; aux yeux de lynx, toute la Cour des Miracles, envahissait le Mont-Saint- Michel. Ils &eacute;taient, cependant, sous la surveillance de la police: c&apos;est ainsi que ces boh&eacute;miens &eacute;taient tenus de faire des d&eacute;clarations de changement de domicile ou de r&eacute;sidence, quand ils se transportaient d&apos;un lieu dans <font color="green">[215]</font> un autre. Une loi r&eacute;cente oblige maintenant les nomades, m&ecirc;me d&apos;origine fran&ccedil;aise, &agrave; faire viser leurs carnets d&apos;identit&eacute; par les maires et la gendarmerie. Un curieux registre, d&eacute;pos&eacute; aux Archives de la Loire- Inf&eacute;rieure, nous apprend qu&apos;en 1509, les autorit&eacute;s de Nantes d&eacute;livr&egrave;rent un passeport &agrave; &ldquo;Guillaume de la Roque, Capitaine de la Petite Egypte, pour se rendre de Nantes au Mont-Saint-Michel, en se logeant dans les faubourgs des villes et des bourgades&raquo;. Il lui &eacute;tailt fait expresse d&eacute;fense d&apos;extravaguer, c&apos;est-&agrave;-dire de vagabonder ou plut&ocirc;t de passer par des endroits autres que ceux port&eacute;s sur le permis de circulation. Naturellement il se glissait, parmi ces Egyptiens, des filous et des voleurs; aussi les plaintes de leurs victimes &eacute;taient-elles fr&eacute;quentes; on d&eacute;couvrait quelquefois ces malandrins, mais on mettait rarement la main sur les bourses d&eacute;rob&eacute;es ou quand on retrouvait celles-ci sur le pav&eacute; de la rue, elles &eacute;taient vides. Cela se reproduit encore maintenant. <p>Les p&egrave;lerins se plaignaient aussi des goglus. Les goglus n&apos;&eacute;taient autres que les pisteurs, les insupportables pisteurs de nos jours. Goglu, d&apos;apr&egrave;s Littr&eacute;, est d&apos;origine incertaine; ce philologue, aussi &eacute;rudit que prudent, aimait mieux ne rien dire du tout que de dire une b&ecirc;tise. Nos &eacute;tymologistes actuels trouvent, dans le mot <font color="green">[216]</font> goglu, la racine celtique gog qui impliquerait une id&eacute;e de fraude ou de tromperie. Quoiqu&apos;il en soit, le chroniqueur Thomas Le Roy signale, en mai 1646, l&apos;effronterie de ces vilains personnages. Il nous montre l&apos;archidiacre du Mont faisant, &agrave; cette date, des remontrances &agrave; plusieurs bourgeois de la ville unis &agrave; certains goglus, lesquels leur amenaient des p&egrave;lerins et, par ce moyen, &ocirc;taient &agrave; ceux-ci la libert&eacute; deloger o&ugrave; bon leur semblait. <p>Le gogluage &eacute;tait un d&eacute;lit; c&apos;&eacute;tait aussi un p&eacute;ch&eacute;; pour &ecirc;tre absous, il fallait passer par le tribunal de la P&eacute;nitence &ldquo;Le r&eacute;v&eacute;rend p&egrave;re archidiacre, nous apprend Thomas Le Roy, a rendu une sentence aux termes de laquelle il d&eacute;fend le gogluage et se r&eacute;serve de donner l&apos;absolution des cas commis par les d&eacute;linquants et fait d&eacute;fense &agrave; tous les confesseurs du Mont de les absoudre.&raquo; C&apos;&eacute;tait un cas r&eacute;serv&eacute;; les th&eacute;ologiens d&apos;aujourd&apos;hui sont-ils aussi s&eacute;v&egrave;res et le cas est-il aussi fr&eacute;quent? <br> <font color="green">[The crowd descends, tumultuous and noisy, toward the hostels; it flows through the narrow street; it follows the ramparts, those who go up to the abbey, meet those who come out of it; in the narrow passages, at sharp turns, along the stairs, these encounters become collisions. All those conversations produce a strange murmur: suddenly a cry is heard: &ldquo;Thief! Thief, someone has taken my purse!&rdquo; &hellip; Let me comfort you, madam. In the Middle Ages, there were sisters of misfortune; in the long-gone days of the pilgrimages, the Little Egypt also assailed the masses devoted to the Archangel: jugglers, clowns, pickpockets, the fake lame, the blind &hellip; with eyes of a lynx, all of the Court of Miracles was in Mont-Saint-Michel. They were under surveillance of the police: this is why the bohemians were supposed to declare a change of address or of residence, when they went from one place to another. A recent law now obliges the nomads, even when they are French citizens, to have their identity cards checked by the mayor and the gendarmes. A curious register, at the Archives of Loire-Inf&eacute;rieure, teaches us that in 1509, the authorities of Nantes gave a passport to &ldquo;William de la Roque, Capitain of Little Egypt, to go from Nantes to Mont-Saint-Michel, while stopping in the suburbs of the cities and villages.&rdquo; He was &ldquo;expressly forbidden to extravaguer, i.e. to be a vagabond or to pass through places that were not mentioned on his circulation permit. Naturally, scum and thieves sneaked among the Egyptians, scum and thieves; the complaints of their victims were frequent enough; one sometimes caught these robbers, but it was difficult to find the purses that had been stolen and when they were found on the pavement of the street, they were empty. That still happens today. <p>The pilgrims also complained of the goglus. These were not other than pisteurs, the unbearable pisteurs of today. Goglu, according to Littr&eacute;, is of uncertain origin; that philologue, as erudite as he was prudent, would rather say nothing than say something stupid. Our current etymologists find, in the word goglu, the Celtic root gog which implies a sense of fraud or deception. However that may be, already in 1646, Thomas Le Roy writes about the crimes of these bad people. He shows how the archdeacon of the Mont blamed several burhers of the town for giving shelter to these gogglues, who brought them pilgrims, and thus also the freedom to stay wherever they wanted. <p>Gogluage was a crime; it was also a sin; in order to be redeemed one had to pass through the tribunal of Penitence &ldquo;The reverend father archdeacon, Thomas Le Roy tells us, has given a sentence he forbids gogluage and he reserves the right to absolve these cases committed by delinquents and he forbids all the confessors of the Mont to absolve them.&rdquo; It was a reserved case: are the theologians today as severe and is the case still so common?]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 215-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
